etween this public disavowal and the maintenance of hierarchy and authority within the movement. This study analyses how this contradiction is then reproduced in different micro-social interactions, examining the methods by which people negotiate minute details of their daily lives as squatter activists in the face of a fun house mirror of ideological expectations reflecting values from within the squatter community, that, in turn, often refract mainstream, middle-class norms.Using a unique critical perspective informed by gender and subaltern studies, this study contributes to social movements literature through a meticulous analysis of the production of power and hierarchy in a social movement subculture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnology. Social and cultural anthropology. 0aSocialism. Communism. Anarchism. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Anarchism.2bisacsh  aactivism.  aanthropology.  aautonomy.  aethnography.  ahabitus.  ahierarchy.  aparticipant observation.  aradical left.  asquatters movement.  asubcultural capital.1 aKadir, Nazima, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781784997564zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784997564zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784997564/original  a978-3-11-128282-4 Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA